data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration is needed here.**

Your code only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — none of which are affected by the .NET 6+ breaking change. These APIs work identically in modern .NET, so this code will compile and run correctly as-is on .NET 8.

### Optional modernization (unrelated to Thread.Abort)

You *could* modernize to `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run` for cleaner code, but this is **not required** for the migration:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, item => Process(item));
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This is purely a style/ergonomics improvement — your existing code is already .NET 8 compatible.
